---
import "../styles/global.css";
import BaseHead from "../components/BaseHead.astro";
import Header from "../components/Header.astro";
import Footer from "../components/Footer.astro";

const title = "Ethics, Risks, and Future Paths for Creative AI";
const description =
  "Looking at the ethical concerns around AI in art and creativity, and possible ways to use it responsibly.";
---

<html lang="en">
  <head>
    <BaseHead title={title} description={description} />
  </head>

  <body>
    <div class="bg-orb"></div>
    <Header />
    <main>
      <section>
        <h1>{title}</h1>
        <p class="lead">
          AI supports creativity, but it also raises serious problems. As generative systems spread
          into art, design, writing, and music, they raise questions about authorship, bias, job
          security, and the long-term health of culture.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>Challenges in Ethics</h2>

        <h3>1. Genuineness and Worth</h3>
        <p>
          If a picture or a song appears in seconds, does human effort lose value? Many artists fear
          that speed will replace skill and feeling. Even when AI output looks polished, there is a
          worry that it will <strong>lower the perceived value</strong> of human creativity and make
          years of practice seem less important. Some researchers describe this as
          <span class="tech-term"> creative displacement anxiety</span>.
        </p>

        <h3>2. AI System Bias</h3>
        <p>
          Models learn from data taken from the real world, which means they also absorb
          <strong>real-world stereotypes</strong>. Generated pictures often show cultural bias,
          repeat the same items, and over-represent certain races or body types while pushing others
          out of view. Without regular checks, AI can quietly spread a narrow view of who and what
          “belongs” in art.
        </p>

        <h3>3. Visual Uniformity</h3>
        <p>
          Over time AI images start to look alike. The same styles, lighting setups, and color
          palettes keep coming back. Long-term studies show that while content variety can increase,
          <strong>visual originality tends to drop</strong>. If everyone uses the same models and
          prompt patterns, culture slowly turns more uniform.
        </p>

        <h3>4. Ownership and Copyright</h3>
        <p>
          Who owns AI art? The person who wrote the prompt? The company that trained the model? The
          original artists whose work was scraped into the training data? Many systems were trained
          on existing artworks <strong>without clear consent</strong>, which has led to court cases
          and arguments about copyright, fair use, and creative ownership.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>Potential Future Solutions</h2>
        <p>
          Researchers, artists, and policymakers have suggested several steps for more responsible
          use of creative AI:
        </p>

        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>Treat AI as a partner, not a replacement:</strong> Keep humans in charge of
            direction, taste, and meaning, instead of handing full control to the model.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Stronger copyright rules:</strong> Update law and platform policies so using
            creative work for training without consent is properly addressed, and original authors
            stay protected.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Bias checks:</strong> Regularly test models for demographic and cultural bias,
            then adjust training data or outputs when patterns show up.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Fair compensation:</strong> Build systems where artists can opt in, opt out, or
            get paid when their work is used to train or inspire AI.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Honest communication:</strong> Clearly label AI-generated content so people know
            what they are seeing or hearing, and teach users where AI fails and where it still needs
            improvement.
          </li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>A Human-Centered Future</h2>
        <p>
          The best path is <strong>human plus machine</strong>, not human versus machine. AI should
          help people create, explore, and express themselves in new ways instead of pushing human
          artists out of the picture. That means keeping human creativity at the center of the
          workflow and using AI as a powerful assistant.
        </p>

        <div class="final-note">
          <p>
            If society can align laws, platforms, and norms with that idea, AI could help more
            people participate in creative culture without erasing what makes human art unique:
            <strong>emotion</strong>, <strong>intention</strong>, and
            <strong>lived experience</strong>.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>
    </main>
    <Footer />
  </body>
</html>
